  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-title">What is the Elo Rating System?</h2>
    <div class="text-content">
      <p>The Elo rating system, created by Arpad Elo, is a method for calculating the relative skill levels of players in competitive games. It’s used in chess, esports, and more to provide fair matchmaking and evaluate performance.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2 class="section-title">How Does Elo Work at Chessy.gg?</h2>
    <div class="text-content">
      <h3>1. Pre-Game Expectations</h3>
      <p>Before each match, the system calculates the expected outcome based on player ratings:</p>
      <ul class="steps-list">
        <li>Higher-rated players are expected to win more often.</li>
        <li>Lower-rated players earn more points if they win.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>2. Calculating Expectations</h3>
      <p>The expected scores for each player are calculated using the formula:</p>
      <pre class="code-snippet">
E_A = 1 / (1 + 10^((R_B - R_A) / 400))
E_B = 1 / (1 + 10^((R_A - R_B) / 400))
      </pre>
      <p>
        Where:
        <ul>
          <li><code>E_A</code> is Player A's expected score</li>
          <li><code>R_A</code> is Player A's rating</li>
          <li><code>R_B</code> is Player B's rating</li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <h3>3. Adjusting Ratings</h3>
      <p>After the match, the actual outcome is compared to the expected outcome, and ratings are adjusted accordingly:</p>
      <pre class="code-snippet">
R_A' = R_A + K * (S_A - E_A)
R_B' = R_B + K * (S_B - E_B)
      </pre>
      <p>
        Where:
        <ul>
          <li><code>S_A</code> is Player A's actual score (1 for a win, 0.5 for a draw, 0 for a loss)</li>
          <li><code>K</code> is the adjustment factor (usually 20 for Chessy.gg)</li>
        </ul>
      </p>

      <h3>4. Scenarios</h3>
      <p>Let’s break it down with examples:</p>
      <ul class="examples-list">
        <li><strong>Win:</strong> A lower-rated player defeating a higher-rated opponent earns more points.</li>
        <li><strong>Draw:</strong> A draw results in a smaller rating adjustment for both players.</li>
        <li><strong>Loss:</strong> A higher-rated player loses fewer points when defeated by a lower-rated opponent.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

